<DIV1>
<PB REF="4">
<HEAD>THE VILLAGE LAWYER.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>A Room in</HI> Scout<HI>'s Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>(Without.)</HI> Mrs. Scout.</STAGE>
<P>I Tell you it &s;hall be&mdash;</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Na! na! but my Dear, now!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>It does not &s;ignify talking&mdash;I mu&s;t and will have it &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>But think, my Dear, how ridiculous&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't care&mdash;I'm re&s;olv'd&mdash;I'll no longer be the laughing Stock of the whole Country; do you imagine I'll&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mr. Scout. Mrs. Scout <HI>following.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay! but my dear &s;weet Love, that inde|fatigable
<PB N="6" REF="5">
Tongue of yours, would out-talk any Law|yer in the Kingdom; I can talk &s;ometimes pretty well my&s;elf, but I &s;tand no chance with you&mdash;why, you would out-din the whole Bar it&s;elf, that tho' a Lawyer&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Sneering.)</STAGE>
<P>A Lawyer! No one to &s;ee you in this Trim, would imagine you had ever carried a Cau&s;e in any Body's Suit but your own&mdash;had you a grain of Spirit left, you might&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Spirit! Nay, nay, Wife, don't complain of my want of Spirit; Was it not my Spirit that drove me from the Capital, and make me bury my Talents in Ob&s;curity? Have not I attended all the Harangues of the Courts with only a little Whizzing on one &s;ide, and a Deafne&s;s on the other? And have not I con|vinced you I had too much Spirit on a certain Oc|ca&s;ion?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very fine indeed,&mdash;And &s;o you make a Merit of your Blunders.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Blunders, indeed!&mdash;I think I made a Blun|der in coming here&mdash;Not a &s;ingle Job have I got &s;ince I have been down; not a broken Head, nor a Quarrel for one to get a Penny by&mdash;there has not been a Ba&s;tard born &s;ince we have been here! And, Damn me, if I don't think the very Cattle keep out of the Pound on purpo&s;e to &s;pite me. Now, if one could put on the Appearance of Bu&s;ine&s;s, the Rea|lity will follow of Cour&s;e, and perhaps &s;omething may turn out.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="6">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and in the mean Time, your poor Wife may &s;tarve, and your Daughter lo&s;e the Opportunity of &s;ettling her&s;elf hand&s;omely with one of the young Men that pay their Addre&s;&s;es to her; which the Shabbine&s;s of your Appearance has fright|ened away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to be &s;ure, I am Shabby enough of all Con&s;cience, and cannot with any Propriety make my Appearance in Public.&mdash;Let me &s;ee&mdash;I have it&mdash;I'll go and purcha&s;e a Suit of Clothes directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Purcha&s;e a Suit of Clothes without a Shilling in your Pocket?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, my Dear, that's nothing at all: mo&s;t of the fa&s;hionable Suits in London are purcha&s;|ed that way. Let me &s;ee&mdash;what Colour &s;hall I chu&s;e? &s;hall it be a Brown&mdash;a Grey&mdash;a Bat's-wing&mdash;or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! never mind the Colour, &s;o you can only find &s;omebody Fool enough to let you have the Cloth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, I'll warrant you. Let me &s;ee now&mdash;There's Neighbour Snarl now, that lives over the Way, he keeps a large A&s;&s;ortment of Colours, I'll hum him out of a Suit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Snarl!&mdash;take care what you do there, Hu&s;band; his Son, Charles, is in Love with our Harriot, and would have married her before now, but for fear of his Father's Anger&mdash;I would not for the World di&s;appoint the Girl's hopes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="7">
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! well! &s;tep in and bring my Gown and Band&mdash;it will, at lea&s;t, make me have a better Appearance, <STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Mrs. Scout.</STAGE> by hiding the&s;e damned Rags of mine.&mdash;Come, Wife, make ha&s;te&mdash;take care you don't break the China Ba&s;on on the Window.&mdash;Come, what a long Time you are.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. Scout.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I brought it as &s;oon as I could.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come&mdash;help me on with it&mdash;take Care what you are about. See what a large Hole here is. You &s;it all Day with your Hands before you&mdash;and I think you might have mended it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll mend it when you come back,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>There&mdash;there&mdash;now I &s;hall do very well! and let me tell you, Wife, I am not the only one that make u&s;e of a Gown to hide Things that are not fit to be &s;een.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2">
<PB N="9" REF="8">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Snarl<HI>'s Shop</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Snarl, <HI>and</HI> Charles <HI>following.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charles, have you been looking out for another Shepherd, as I told you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Charles.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, I think you have got a very good one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;uch Thing&mdash;I tell you that Sheep|face is a Rogue&mdash;Here he has lived with me only a Fortnight, and there are mi&s;&s;ing Fourteen of my be&s;t Weathers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Charles.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ider, Sir, what Havock &s;uch a Di&s;|order makes in a little Time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Yes,&mdash;I have con&s;idered&mdash;and I know pretty well by this Time. I have long &s;u&s;pected him&mdash;and la&s;t Night I caught him in the very Fact, killing one of my fatte&s;t Weathers; and am de|termined to have him up before Ju&s;tice Mittimus this Day&mdash;but reach me my Book, and let me look over the Account of my Flock, perhaps there may be more Mi&s;&s;ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Charles.</SPEAKER>
<P>There it is, Sir.</P>
<STAGE>(gives an Account Book.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Sits down.)</STAGE>
<P>And if Neighbour Gripe call, tell him I want to talk with him about this Ra&s;cal, Sheepface.&mdash;Let me &s;ee&mdash;Twelve times Ten</P>
<PB N="10" REF="9">
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sheepface <HI>behind.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Charles.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sheepface&mdash;my Father has di&s;covered all&mdash;do the be&s;t you can, beware &s;aying too much.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Charles.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Save you, good Ma&s;ter Snarl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! you Ra&s;cal! are you here? how dare you appear before me after the Trick you play'd me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only to tell you, I've been with Neigh|bour Gripe, the Con&s;table, who has been &s;peaking to me about Sheep-&s;tealing, Ju&s;tice Mittimus, your Honour, and a power of Things&mdash;&s;o I &s;aid to my|&s;elf, as how I would not make it a Secret any longer with your good Work&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why! Fellow! this affected Simplicity won't &s;erve your Purpo&s;e.&mdash;Did not I catch you la&s;t Night killing one of my fatte&s;t Weathers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only to keep it from Dying, by my Feckins.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>To keep it from Dying!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Of the Rot, an plea&s;e your &s;weet Wor|&s;hip&mdash;it's a Way I learnt of our Doctor in the Pari&s;h, he cures mo&s;t of his Patients the &s;ame Way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>the Doctor, ha! the Doctors have a Li|&s;ence to kill from the College, but you have none, I believe. Why! there was not &s;uch a Breed in all the Kingdom for Spani&s;h Wool!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="10">
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plea&s;e your Wor&s;hip, &s;atisfy your&s;elf with the Blows you gave me, and make Matters up, if it be your Wor&s;hip's good Will and Plea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>But 'tis not my good Will and Plea&s;ure&mdash;my good Will and Plea&s;ure is to &s;ee you hanged, you Ra&s;cal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! no; don't hang me!&mdash;con&s;ider that would be the Death of me! be&s;ides, your Wor&s;hip, I was only married Ye&s;terday&mdash;leave me alone for a Week or two, and who knows, but by that Time, I may &s;ave your Wor&s;hip the Trouble.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, the Gallows will be the be&s;t Way at fir&s;t, and every bit as &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven give you the Luck of it, good Ma&s;ter Snarl.&mdash;Since it mu&s;t be &s;o, I mu&s;t go &s;eek for a Lawyer, I find, or Might will prevail over Right.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Sheepface.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Six times Twelve is Seventy-two&mdash;that is Right&mdash;then Nine times Seven is&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Scout.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad! I have nick'd it nicely!&mdash;this was very lucky to catch him alone.&mdash;That &s;eems to be a pretty piece of Cloth, and will ju&s;t &s;uit me. Good Morning to you, Mr. Snarl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>O! what Neighbour Gripe! walk in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, it's I, your Neighbour Scout.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="11">
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am my Neighbour Scout's mo&s;t obedient&mdash;but I have no Bu&s;ine&s;s with him, at pre&s;ent, that I know of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<P>I'll make you tell a different Story pre&s;ently, or I am much mi&s;taken.&mdash;I call'd to &s;ettle a little Account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have no Account to &s;ettle with any body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is a &s;mall Ballance of fifty Pounds&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know nothing at all about it; I don't owe any Man a Farthing in the World.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I could &s;ay as much for my&s;elf, <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Why, Sir, looking over my Father's Ac|counts, I &s;ee he &s;tands indebted to you fifty Pounds; and I, asan hone&s;t Man, am come to pay it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Turning round, ri&s;es, and &s;hakes him by the Hand.)</STAGE>
<P>How do you do, Neighbour Scout? How do you do? I'm glad to &s;ee you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, I thank you, Sir. How do you do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think you live in our Village here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray be &s;eated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no Means, I fcar I di&s;turb you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! no, not at all, pray &s;it down&mdash;I in|&s;i&s;t upon it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! Sir, if every body was of my Prin|ciple, I &s;hould be a deal richer than I am; I cannot bear to be in any body's Debt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="12">
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why? egad! the Generality of People bear it very well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true, Sir, very true; when would you like to receive this Money? for I am impatient to pay every body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, when you plea&s;e.&mdash;No Time like the Time pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true; I have it told out at home; but as I only hold my Father's Effects in Tru&s;t for my Daughter Harriot, for Form &s;ake, you know it will be proper to have &s;ome of the other Guardians pre&s;ent at the Time of Payment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true, it is &s;o indeed!&mdash;Well, as &s;oon as you plea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you think of Three o'Clock this Afternoon?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very good Time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, egad! it happens very lucky&mdash;I have got a very fine Goo&s;e &s;ent me by a Client from Norfolk, and you &s;hall come and dine with me.&mdash;Are you fond of Goo&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very. It's my favourite Di&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's very lucky. Don't forget to come. I think you do a deal of bu&s;ine&s;s here; more than all the Re&s;t of the Trade around the Country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pretty well; I can't complain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>And Mrs. Scout will dre&s;s the Goo&s;e by a valuable Receipt left her by her Great Uncle Al|derman Dumpling.&mdash;Do you like it with Sage and Onion?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very much, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall have it &s;o. Why, you have &s;uch an engaging Way with you, that People take more Plea&s;ure in paying you Money, than in re|ceiving it from other People.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Sir, you &s;latter me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not at all.&mdash;Egad! now I recollect&mdash;I promi&s;ed Mr. Scout &s;hould have my Cu&s;tom; and I don't care if I take a Coat to begin with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Sir, look over my Pattern's, here's a Variety of Colours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;eems to be a pretty Piece of Cloth.</P>
<STAGE>(Feeling the Cloth that lies on the Counter.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very fine, and good!&mdash;It's an Iron Grey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you remember our going to School together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! along with old Iron Fi&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;ame. You was reckoned the pretti$&s;t boy in the whole &s;chool.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes? my Mother &s;aid I always was a pretty boy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>This Cloth &s;eems very &s;mooth and fine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Right Spani&s;h Wool I a&s;&s;ure you!&mdash;Let, me &s;end your Quantity to your Hou&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop! &s;top!&mdash;Pay as you go&mdash;pay as you go!&mdash;That is always my Maxim.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, egad, a very good Maxim 'tis!&mdash;I Wi&s;h all my Cu&s;tomers made U&s;e of the &s;ame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you remember the tricks you u&s;ed to play the Curate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, very well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, you was always full of mi&s;ch&s;ef&mdash;what is this Cloth a yard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why to any body el&s;e it &s;hould be Nine|teen Shillings and Sixpence, but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now you are going to favour me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I am not; only as you are a particular friend, I won't charge you but Nineteen&mdash;And luckily here is ju&s;t your quantity cut off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's lucky, I'll take it home with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no means; my Boy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why would you take the poor Boy from his Work? I don't mind carrying it my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, let me mea&s;ure it; perhaps there may be &s;ome Mi&s;take?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>No mi&s;take&mdash;dy'e think I doubt your word,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>But the price!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never mind that, I leave it entirely to you.&mdash;Well, good Morning&mdash;Don't forget the Goo&s;e:&mdash;You'll be &s;ure to be there Time enough to dine, before you receive your Money. Good Morn|ing&mdash;Don't forget.</P>
<STAGE>[Eit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Demme but he's carried off my cloth.&mdash;But he'll pay: O yes, he'll pay; for he mu&s;t be a very hone&s;t Man, or he never would have told me of the fifty Pounds, and invite me to dine off the Goo&s;e into the Bargain. I am &s;orry I cheated him in the
<PB N="16" REF="15">
Cloth&mdash;but no Matter; it is the Way I got all my Money.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sheepface <HI>and</HI> Kate.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kate.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you wants a Lawyer to get you fairly out of a Scrape, my Ma&s;ter's the Man for your Money, Sheepface.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>I remember he &s;tood my Friend before, from being hanged at York!&mdash;and, would you be|lieve it, only for mending the Complexion of a bald faced Hor&s;e; and I don't know how it was, I have &s;uch a treacherous Memory: but &s;ome how or other&mdash;I forgot to pay him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kate.</SPEAKER>
<P>O never mind&mdash;he won't remember that; but be very careful not to tell him your Ma&s;ter's Name.&mdash;I know he would not be concerned again&s;t Mr. Snarl, for the World!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no&mdash;I'll only tell him 'tis my Ma&s;ter, and he'll think I mean the rich Farmer I lived with formerly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kate.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well&mdash;that will do&mdash;but here he comes, I'll go in.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit Kate.</STAGE>
<PB N="17" REF="16">
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Scout.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad I think I have made a good Morn|ing's Work!&mdash;This cloth will enable me to make a genteel Appearance.&mdash;But who have we here? &s;ure I &s;hould know that Face.&mdash;Hark ye, Sir!&mdash;Didn't I &s;ave you and your Brother from being hanged &s;ome Time ago, at York?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>And by the &s;ame Rule, I think one of you forgot to pay me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>That was Brother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>One of you got off clear, and the other died &s;oon after in Pri&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>That was not I!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no&mdash;I &s;ee it was not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>For all that I was &s;icker than my Brother;&mdash;but I am come to a&s;k your Wor&s;hip to &s;tand my Friend again&s;t a&mdash;his Wor&s;hip, my Ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! the rich Farmer here, that lives in the Neighbourhood?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Shep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes&mdash;he lives in the Neighbourhood &s;ure enough;&mdash;and if you will &s;tand my Friend, you &s;hall be paid to your Heart's Content.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye! Now you &s;peak to the Purpo&s;e:&mdash;Come, you mu&s;t tell me how it was.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you mu&s;t know my Ma&s;ter gives me
<PB N="18" REF="17">
but &s;mall Wages&mdash;very &s;mall Wages indeed!&mdash;So I thought I might as well do a little Bu&s;ine&s;s on my own Account, and &s;o make my&s;elf Amends without any Damage to him, with an hone&s;t Neighbour of mine&mdash;a little Bit of a Butcher by Trade.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! But what Bu&s;ine&s;s can you have to do with him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, &s;aving your Wor&s;hip's Pre&s;ence&mdash;I hinders the Sheep from dying of the Rot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah!&mdash;How do you contrive that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cuts their Throats before it comes to them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>What!&mdash;I &s;uppo&s;e then your Ma&s;ter thinks that you kill his Sheep for the &s;ake of &s;elling their Carca&s;&s;es?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and I cannot beat it out of his Head for the Soul of me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well; then you mu&s;t tell me all the parti|culars about it.&mdash;Relate every Circum&s;tance, and don't hide a &s;ingle Item.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, then Sir, you mu&s;t know&mdash;that la&s;t Night, as I was going down,&mdash;(Mu&s;t I tell the Truth?)&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes&mdash;You mu&s;t tell the Truth here, or we &s;hall never be able to lie to the Purpo&s;e any where el&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well then&mdash;La&s;t Night after I was mar|ried, having a little lei&s;ure Time upon my Hands, I goes down to our Penn, and as I was mu&s;ing on I
<PB N="19" REF="18">
don't know what, out I takes my Knife, and hap|pening by mere accident, &s;aving your Wor&s;hip's pre&s;ence, to put it under the throat of one of the fatte&s;t Wethers; I don't know how it came about, but I had not been long there, before the Wether died, and all of a &s;udden, as a Body may &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! and &s;omebody was looking on all the while?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Ma&s;ter from behind the Hedge, and would have it, it died all along with me.&mdash;And &s;o as you &s;ee&mdash;he laid &s;uch a Shower of Blows on me, that it kept the Bride out of Temper all Night&mdash;But I hope your Wor&s;hip will &s;tand my Friend, and not let me lo&s;e the Fruits of my hone&s;t Labour&mdash;all at once.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, there are two Ways of &s;ettling this Bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;and one is, I think, to be done without putting you to any Expence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let's try that fir&s;t by all Means.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have &s;craped up &s;omething in your Ma&s;ter's Service?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been up late and early for it, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e you have taken Care to have your Savings all in hard Ca&s;h?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, then, when you go Home, take it and hide it in the &s;afe&s;t Place you can find.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, that I'll do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll take Care your Ma&s;ter &s;hall pay all Co&s;ts $$d Charges.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="19">
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, &s;o he ought&mdash;he can afford it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;hall be nothing out of your Pocket.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's ju&s;t as I would have it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>He'll have all the Trouble and the Expence of bringing you to Trial, and after that have the Plea&s;ure of &s;eeing you hanged.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let's take the other Way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well!&mdash;let me &s;ee&mdash;I &s;uppo&s;e he'll take out a Warant again&s;t you, and have you taken before Ju&s;tice Mittimus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>So I under&s;tand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think the Ju&s;tice's Credulity is ea&s;ily im|po&s;ed on:&mdash;&s;o when you are ordered before him, I'll attend, and to all the Que&s;tions that you are a&s;ked, an&s;wer nothing, but imitate the Voice of the Lambs, when they bleat afte the Ewes&mdash;You can &s;peak that Dialect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's my Mother Tongue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>But if I bring you off clear, I expect to be very well paid for this.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>So you &s;hall&mdash;I'll pay you to your Heart's Content.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;ure you an&s;wer nothing but Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye! that will do very well&mdash;Be &s;ure &s;tick to that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheep.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, your Wor&s;hip&mdash;Never fear I&mdash;What Trouble a Body has to keep one's own in this World.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt &s;everally.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4">
<PB N="21" REF="20">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The Out&s;ide of</HI> Scout's <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Snarl.</STAGE>
<P>Aye, aye&mdash;that's my Neighbour Scout's Hou&s;e&mdash;he is ju&s;t come Home to give orders about the Din|ner, I warrant&mdash;Egad, I think I &s;hall make a good Day's Work&mdash;What with the Fifty Pounds his Fa|ther owed mine&mdash;which, by the bye, I know no|thing at all about&mdash;and the money for the Cloth&mdash;and the Goo&s;e that is to be dre&s;s'd by a famous Re|ceipt from Alderman Dumpling's.&mdash;Egad, I be|lieve they are dre&s;&s;ing it now&mdash;I'll in, and &s;ee what is going forward.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5">
<PB N="22" REF="21">
<HEAD>SCENE V.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The In&s;ide of</HI> Sout's <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Scout, Mrs. Scout <HI>following.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wife, wife&mdash;come along&mdash;I think I hear Snarl at the Door: come to your Place, and mind your Cue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear me&mdash;I warrant I &s;hall make an excellent Nur&s;e.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Snarl.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where is my Friend Mr. Scout?&mdash;Is the Goo&s;e a Dre&s;&s;ing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wife, Wife&mdash;Here comes the Doctor&mdash;he brings me the cooling Mixture&mdash;the cooling Mix|ture!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>The cooling Mixture!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir! I hope you have brought &s;omething for my poor Hu&s;band; he has been con|fined to his Room, and has not been out this Fort|night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="23" REF="22">
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not out of his Room this Fortnight!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, This Day Fortnight, of all the good Days in the Year, he was &s;eized with a Lunacy Fit, and has not been out of Doors, &s;ince.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Woman! What are you talk|ing about?&mdash;Why he came to my Shop this Morn|ing, and by the &s;ame Token, bought four Yards of Iron Grey Cloth, and I am come for my Money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>This Morning!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>This Morning! and invited me to dine with him To-day off a Goo&s;e, and to receive fifty Pounds which his Father owed mine.&mdash;I'll &s;peak to him&mdash;How d'ye do, good Mr. Scout?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! how d'ye do good Mr. Drench?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good Mr. Drench!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>He takes you for the Doctor, Mr. Drench.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wife, Wife&mdash;keep the Doctor frome me, and a Fig for the Di&s;ea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>For Heaven's Sake, Sir, if you can't relieve him, don't torment him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your Tongue Woman. I want my Cloth or my Money. Mr. Scout!&mdash;Mr. Scout!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>See! &s;ee! &s;ee!&mdash;there is three nice Butter|&s;lies, there they fly! there they fly! <STAGE>(Jumps after them)</STAGE> with b$t wings.&mdash;I've batch'd them&mdash;I have them&mdash;I have them&mdash;Tally-ho, Tally-ho!&mdash;Oh! oh! oh!</P>
<STAGE>(falls in the Chair).</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="23">
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Butterflies!&mdash;Damme if I can &s;ee any.&mdash;I wi&s;h to &s;ee my Cloth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Jumps on the Chair.)</STAGE>
<P>My Lord, and Gen|tlemen of the Jury&mdash;My Client Sir Hugh Wither|ington, charges the Defendant Mr. Mungummery,&mdash;that is moreover, neverthele&s;s, as &s;hall appear as&mdash;<STAGE>(&s;pits at him)&mdash;(Jumps down and dances)</STAGE>&mdash;Dol! de rol de lol! Oh! oh! oh!&mdash;<STAGE>(Jumps cro&s;s-legg'd o$ the $Word$).</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>There now, he's fancying him&s;elf a Tay|l$$, and at Work upon my Cloth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do, pray Sir, leave him, and don't torment him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't leave him without my Money&mdash;See he is getting better.&mdash;I'll &s;peak to him again.&mdash;How d'ye do neighbour Scout?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>How d'ye do Mr. Snarl?&mdash;I am glad to &s;ee you,&mdash;I hope you are very well? My dear here is Mr. Snarl come to &s;ee us!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>There! there! there! he knows me&mdash;he knows me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Mr. Snarl, I beg a thou&s;and pardons; I confe&s;s I have been very unkind; but I hope you'l excu&s;e me for not coming to &s;ee you. I have never called on you &s;ince I come to live in this Part of the Country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never called on me! Oh, the Devil! I &s;hall never get my Cloth again.&mdash;Why Man you called on me this Morning, and bought four Yards
<PB N="25" REF="24">
of Iron Grey Cloth, and I am come for my Money. Be&s;ides fifty Pounds your Father owed mine&mdash;Aye&punc; you may &s;hake your head; but dam'me If I go out of the Hou&s;e without it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say you &s;o? then I'll try &s;ome thing el&s;e. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Wife! Wife! Wife! get up&mdash;&s;oftly! &s;oftly! get up!&mdash;don't lie &s;noring there&mdash;there's Thieves in the Hou&s;e. No, no.&mdash;Second Thoughts, be &s;till, while I fetch my Gun and &s;hoot them. Cover your&s;elf up clo&s;e; I'll &s;hoot them! &s;hoot them! &s;hoot them!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thieves in the Hou&s;e did he &s;ay? Egad&punc; who knows but in his mad Tricks, he may &s;hoot me for a Thief? I'll get out of his Way, and not &s;tay with a Madman.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Scout <HI>with a Birch Broom, and pre&s;ents it at him. Boh!</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>[Exit Snarl.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Victoria! Victoria!&mdash;Huzza.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt Mr. and Mrs. Scout.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2">
<PB N="26" REF="25">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Ju&s;tices Office.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Ju&s;tice Mittimus <HI>di&s;covered &s;itting,</HI> Clerks, &amp;c.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;tice.</SPEAKER>
<P>So the Court being a&s;&s;embled the Par|ties may appear.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Snarl, Scout, Sheepface, Con&s;tables, &amp;c.</STAGE>
<P>Where's your Lawyer, neighbour Snarl?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am my own Lawyer, I &s;hall employ no|body, that would co&s;t more Money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, how now you Ra&s;cal, have you im|po&s;ed upon me? What's the meaning of all this? is that the Plaintiff?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide to Scout)</STAGE>
<P>Yes, that's his Honour, my good Ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>O! the Devil! What &s;hall I do? I mu&s;t &s;tay and brazen it out! If I &s;neak out of Court it will cau&s;e &s;u&s;picion.</P>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, neighbour Snarl, begin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well then, that Thief, there&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>No abu&s;e! no abu&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well then, I &s;ay that Ra&s;cal my Shepherd&mdash;
<PB N="27" REF="26">
No&mdash;do my eyes deceive me, &s;ure that is&mdash;yes&mdash;it mu&s;t be he&mdash;if I had not left him very bad I could have &s;worn&mdash;yes, yes, 'tis him, and that other Ra&s;|cal came to my Shop and bought&mdash;No, No,&mdash;I don't mean &s;o&mdash;that Ra&s;cal there has killed fourteen of my fatte&s;t Weathers. What an&s;wer do you make to that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>I deny the fact.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is become of them then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>They did die of the rot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis him&mdash;his Voice too&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>What proof have you got.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why this Morning he came to my hou&s;e&mdash;No, No, I mean I went down la&s;t night to the pens, having long &s;u&s;pected him&mdash;'tis he! 'tis he and he began a long Story about Fifty Pounds, No, No, I don't mean that, and there I caught him in the very fact.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>That remains to be proved.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I'll &s;wear 'tis the very man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why this is the very man, but is it certain that your weathers died of the rot, what an&s;wer do you make to that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I tell you, he came this very morning, and after talking &s;ome time, makes no more to do thancarries off four yards of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Four yards of your weathers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, four yards of my Cloth, I mean that other Thief, that other there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>What other! What other, neighbour Snarl?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="27">
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why he's mad, an plea&s;e your Wor&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Truly I think &s;o too, hark'ye neighbour Snarl, not all the Ju&s;tices in the Country, no nor their Clerks neither, can make any thing of your evidence. Stick to your Weathers! &s;tick to your Weathers! or I mu&s;t relea&s;e the pri&s;oner; but howe|ver I believe it will be the &s;horte&s;t way to examine him my&s;elf, come here my good fellow, hold up your head, don't be frightened, tell me your name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's a lie! it's a lie! His name is Sheepface.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, Sheepface or Baa, no matter for the name, did Mr. Snarl give you in charge four &s;core Sheep, Sheepface?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay did Mr. Snarl catch you in the night killing one of his fatte&s;t Weathers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>What does he mean by Baa?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plea&s;e your Wor&s;hip, the blows he gave this poor fellow on the head has &s;o affected his &s;en&s;es, he can &s;ay nothing el&s;e; he is to be trepann'd as &s;oon as the Court breaks up, and the Doctors &s;ay it is the whole Materia Medica, again&s;t a do&s;e of Jalup, he never recovers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>But the Act, and in that ca&s;e provided, for|bids all blows, particularly on the head.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was dark, and when I &s;trike, I never mind where the blows fall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="28">
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>A voluntary confe&s;&s;ion, a voluntary con|fe&s;&s;ion!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>A voluntary confe&s;&s;ion indeed, relea&s;e the pri&s;oner, I find no cau&s;e of complaint again&s;t him.</P>
<STAGE>[Ri&s;es.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>No cau&s;e of complaint again&s;t him! you are a pretty Ju&s;tice indeed, one kills my Sheep, and the other pays me with Sir Hugh Witherington, and then you can &s;ee no cau&s;e of complaint again&s;t him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not I truly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>A pretty day's work I have made indeed, a Suit of Law, and a Suit of Iron-grey Cloth both carried again&s;t me; but as for you Mr. Lawyer, we &s;hall meet again.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Snarl.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>O fie, neighbour Snarl, you're to blame; very much to blame indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, now it's all over, go and thank his Wor&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa, Baa, Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Enough, enough, my good fellow, take care you don't catch cold in your Head, go and get trepann'd, and take care of your&s;elf, Sheepface.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor fellow! poor fellow!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Ju&s;tice.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo my Boy! you have acted your part admirably, and I think I did very well to bring you off &s;o cleverly; and now I make no doubt but as
<PB N="30" REF="29">
you are a very hone&s;t Fellow, you'll pay me as gene|rous as you promis'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye! very well, very well indeed&mdash;you did that very well ju&s;t now, but there's no occa&s;ion to have it over any more&mdash;I'm talking about my fee you know Sheepface!&mdash;Yes, yes, I tell you it was very well done, but at this time you know my fee is the que&s;tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa, Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>How's this, am I laughed at, pay me di|rectly you Ra&s;cal or I'll play the Devil with you! I'll teach you try to cheat a Lawyer that lives by cheat|ing others, I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>What again! braved by a Mongril Cur, a bleating Bellweather! a&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Out of my &s;ight, or Ill break every bone in your Dog's &s;kin, you Sheep-&s;lealing Scoundrel, would you cheat one that has cheated hundreds? get home to your hiding place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away, and mind how you and your wife play the re&s;t of your parts, and perhaps I may for|give you if we &s;ucceed; if not I will make an exam|ple of you, you Ra&s;cal!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baa, Baa!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Sheepface.</STAGE>
<PB N="31" REF="30">
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Ju&s;tice <HI>and</HI> Kate.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor fellow! Like to die you &s;ay,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kate.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes your Wor&s;hip&mdash;Oh dear!</P>
<STAGE>(crying.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, comfort your&s;elf, remember you was only married Ye&s;terday.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kate.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's the very thing, Sir, if he had but lived a little longer I &s;hould not have cared &s;o much about it, but to be cut off ju&s;t in the Honey Moon is very hard, Oh! Oh! Oh! But I am not re|vengeful, and your Wor&s;hip knows how much I love my Ma&s;ter's Daughter Harriet; and Charles, Mr. Snarl's Son is in love with her, but his Father won't agree to the Match.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, I under&s;tand you, &s;o you'll hu&s;h up matters, provided he'll agree to the Marriage; well, what &s;ay you neighbour Scout.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why! why, I don't know what to &s;ay to it, as you all &s;eem willing to &s;ettle the Bu&s;ine&s;s, I don't like to &s;tand out, and &s;o I agree to it. But I think your Wor&s;hip, I had better go in and fill up the blanks of a Bond and make him &s;ign it, or when all is over he'll retract from his word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well do &s;o! Here he comes, go! go!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Scout <HI>and</HI> Kate,</STAGE>
<PB N="32" REF="31">
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Snarl.</STAGE>
<P>So neighbour Snarl, I find that the blows that you gave the poor Fellow on the Head, has occa&s;ioned his Death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the Devil!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>But hark'ye neighbour, I've got a propo&s;al to make, which perhaps may not be di&s;agreeable to you; your Son Charles it &s;eems is in love with Har|riet, Lawyer Scout's Daughter&mdash;Now, I believe' Sheepface's wife would hu&s;h up matters, provided you'll con&s;ent to the match.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ent! why I &s;uppo&s;e I mu&s;t, in order to &s;ave my&s;elf from further expence, a very pretty day's work I have made on't truly.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Scout.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here your Wor&s;hip, I have filled up a Bond, in order that he may &s;ign whatever is agreed to, how d'ye do neighbour Snarl&mdash;I always cut my Coat&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>According to my Cloth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come! &s;ign, &s;ign!</P>
<STAGE>[Signs the Bond.</STAGE>
<PB N="33" REF="32">
<STAGE>Con&s;table without</STAGE>
<P>Bring him along neighbour Hobnail.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Charles, Sheepface, Con&s;table, &amp;c.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ju&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey dey! where did this fellow come from?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>I come from nece&s;&s;ity your Wor&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Snarl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey dey! What the plague are you not dead?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, your Wor&s;hip could never beat &s;uch a thing into my Head.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Charles.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Sir, don't be angry, Sheepface has done nothing but by my directions, and I hope you'll not only forgive him, but enable me by your future Genero&s;ity to provide for our&s;elves hencefor|ward.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sheepface.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do take back one of your be&s;t Sheep.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Scout.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, as we have &s;ettled our own affairs thus far, we mu&s;t now appeal to the Tribunal, and humbly a&s;k their permi&s;&s;ion for the Village Lawyer, to continue in Practice.</P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
